<TEXT>
eastern airlines says it will appeal a 
contemptofcourt citation imposed by a judge who ruled that plans 
to transfer the airlines shuttle operations to a new corporate 
entity violate a 1987 injunction 
us district judge john h pratt ruled thursday that the 
miamibased airline was in contempt of his july 2 1987 order that 
it maintain the status quo in working conditions for 12000 
employees represented by the international association of 
machinists and aerospace workers 
although the preliminary injunction issued last summer dealt 
with a separate labor dispute pratt said his order also applied to 
any plans to change the working conditions of union workers that 
would create a major dispute as defined by the railway labor act 
the judge scheduled a march 18 hearing to determine what 
sanctions to impose against eastern the judge could impose a daily 
fine to force eastern to halt its plans to transfer the shuttle to 
a new corporate entity under its parent texas air corp 
in a complicated financial deal announced last month texas air 
will purchase the shuttle operation for 225 million the federal 
aviation administration must approve the transaction and give an 
operating certificate to the new operator to take over the shuttle 
which operates between washington new york and boston 
airline spokesman robin matell said easterns view is that the 
courts ruling is incorrect and we intend to file an expedited 
appeal in the us court of appeals for the district of columbia 
we are confident the court will rule in our favor 
the union meanwhile said in a statement that the courts 
order today sends a message to texas air that it is not above the 
law and it too must comply with the railway labor act 
pratt found that the proposed transfer to texas air 
significantly changes the working conditions of iam members 
we find that the proposed spin off of easterns air shuttle 
operations to the new air shuttle is not fundamentally different 
from the proposed spin off of easterns fleet services employees 
to air ground services the judges opinion said 
that spinoff which was barred last summer involved plans to 
transfer ground crews and baggage handlers to a new subsidiary 
called air ground services inc 
easterns serious financial problems do not change the fact 
that it proposed a spin off of the air shuttle is in clear 
violation of our july 2 1987 order which whatever doubts eastern 
had as to its meaning and application it made no attempt to have 
clarified or modified the judge said 
the judge noted that eastern announced the deal a day after it 
dropped its appeal of the preliminary injunction in the air ground 
case 
pratt accepted the unions contention that spinning off the air 
shuttle could undermine the machinists bargaining position with 
the company if fewer than 50 percent of the air shuttles 
employees opt to join the iam machinists who transferred to the 
new subsidiary from eastern would be without union representation 
the judge noted 
the decision is the latest in a series of complicated and often 
bitter legal fights eastern is having with its union 
in a separate action the air line pilots association is trying 
to bar eastern from contracting with an air freight hauler to train 
pilots to operate the companys planes in the event of a strike 
this spring 
the pilots union has asked another federal judge here to issue 
a temporary restraining order to prevent the use of eastern 
aircraft by orion air inc 
so far one plane has been leased to orion to train pilots who 
would fly eastern aircraft in the event the pilots honor a strike 
by the machinists union according to court testimony the union 
contends this arrangement circumvents the labor contract that 
specifies that only its members can operate eastern planes 
eastern contends that the labor agreement does not prevent it 
from leasing its aircraft to other companies 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

