<DOCNO> AP880311-0011 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
president reagan has released a symbolic wish 
list of projects he wants congress to strike from its spending 
plan but there appears little chance capitol hill will pay much 
attention 
james c miller iii director of the office of management and 
budget said that if the list were adopted the savings for fiscal 
1988 alone would amount to 115 billion 
miller who released the list thursday said the money saved 
could be used either to reduce the deficit or pay for more 
meaningful projects 
the items were included in the 600 billion catchall spending 
bill approved at the end of last years congressional session 
im hopeful congress will respond to it miller said when 
asked whether the cuts had any chance of gaining congressional 
attention 
the list which has no legal power has no effect unless 
congress moves to adopt it the presidents request was not in the 
form of legislation and even when he has made such requests 
formally they have received little support in congress 
reagans effort appears to fall short of the pledge he made in 
his state of the union address in january 
in his speech reagan repeated his longstanding request for the 
lineitem veto which would allow him to delete specific items from 
congress spending bills 
in lieu of such power reagan said he intended to send back to 
congress in 30 days those items as rescissions which if i 
had the authority to line them out i would do so 
instead of sending the formal rescissions to congress reagan 
sent the informal list 
miller explained that the president decided not to send the 
formal rescission list because many members of congress had argued 
such an action would upset the bipartisan agreement on the budget 
reached last year by the white house and congress 
this is not an ordinary year miller said referring to the 
lengthy negotiations that produced the budget agreement 
gop sources on capitol hill who spoke on condition of 
anonymity said the strategy was adopted to avoid electionyear 
clashes with republican lawmakers who won spending projects for 
their home districts last year 
in proposing a formal rescission reagan freezes spending on 
those items for 45 days and gives procedural advantages to those in 
congress supporting the effort after the 45day period the 
spending would be restored unless the rescissions were approved 
in his 46page informal list reagan cited a myriad of projects 
from around the country including the construction of a ski lift 
in idaho 15 building projects at universities or medical schools 
and even a program to establish a fund to preserve lighthouses 
sen james mcclure ridaho won approval for 64 million for a 
kellogg idaho gondola in the 600 billion spending bill approved 
late last year the money was in appropriations for a forest 
service program that is supposed to pay for development and 
management of forests 
the 15 construction projects included 4 million for a cancer 
research center at the medical university of south carolina and 
75 million for a pediatric research center at the childrens 
hospital of pittsburgh 
the list also included historic preservation grants with the 
national park service that would establish a bicentennial 
lighthouse fund to distribute matching grants for the preservation 
of lighthouses the list did not give an exact amount for the item 
saying only that it amounted to less than 50000 
