<TEXT>
discovery of a gene that produces a brain 
protein from the chromosome segment responsible for downs syndrome 
puts researchers on the trail of the genetic basis for the most 
common form of mental retardation 
in a study published today in the journal science researchers 
from canada and california report that they have identified a brain 
protein gene in a part of chromosome 21 that relates to downs 
syndrome a discovery that other experts said may be an important 
first step toward a genetic understanding of the birth defect 
it puts bloodhounds on the trail but its still a distant 
scent said dr david r cox of the university of california san 
francisco one of seven scientists who conducted the research he 
cautioned that more study is required because we dont know what 
its relative importance will be in the cause of downs 
dr sigfried pueschel head of a downs syndrome research 
program at brown university and a nationally recognized authority 
said the finding is a significant advance 
it is a first step and an important step pueschel said 
downs syndrome is a congenital defect that includes mental 
retardation and bowel and heart abnormalities downs babies have 
broad features and slanted eyes characteristics that led the 
syndrome to once be identified by the nowobsolete term of 
mongoloidism 
downs syndrome is the most common form of mental retardation 
about 4000 downs babies are born annually in the united states 
the syndrome affects one in every 800 to 1000 live births 
the birth defect is caused by the presence of three copies of 
chromosome 21 instead of the normal pair it is believed that this 
socalled trisomy leads to the genetic expression of proteins 
which in turn lead to the development of downs 
in the science magazine report cox said that his 
coinvestigators found a gene in chromosome 21 that expresses a 
protein called s100 that is primarily found in the brain 
this is the first time that a brain protein has been mapped 
into the downs syndrome region of chromosome 21 he said 
previously there had been some genes that were expressed 
primarily in the brain but those were mapped to other portions 
of the chromosome said cox 
our results say that this is a potential candidate gene that 
may play a major or minor role in mental retardation he said 
it can now be studied to test this hypothesis 
cox emphasized that the discovery offers no immediate promise 
for treatment and that it will take additional study to determine 
the precise effect of the gene 
but it provides the first clue that allows one to start 
looking into that he said 
i think to uncover any gene on chromosome 21 with a specific 
function is a significant advance pueschel said it might in 
the future provide us with information on how to treat these 
individuals 
cox said the researchers isolated portions of chromosome 21 and 
then conducted tests to determine which part produced s100 the 
gene that expressed the protein was found in a band called 21q22 
it is one of perhaps 1000 genes in that portion of chromosome 21 
but cox said it is the first found there that expresses a brain 
protein 
in addition to cox members of the research team were robert 
allore karen neilson hf willard rj dunn david ohanlon and 
alexander marks all of the university of toronto in canada and 
er price of the university of california san francisco 
science is the journal of the american association for the 
advancement of science 
</TEXT>
