<TEXT>
drug and alcohol testing of the nations 
railroad workers is resuming following a court order that has 
temporarily boosted reagan administration efforts to make the 
examinations more common 
the administrator of the federal railroad administration john 
riley told congress on thursday that he had ordered railroads to 
begin conducting the urine and blood tests once again less than a 
month after a federal court in san francisco declared them illegal 
his order was a response to a stay issued last friday that 
temporarily lifts the ban on testing 
if an accident were to occur tomorrow the crew would be 
tested riley told the house transportation appropriations 
subcommittee 
riley said that without last fridays court ruling our 
testing program would be terminated 
the reagan administration has been trying to perform more and 
more drug and alcohol tests on employees in the transportation 
industry 
on feb 11 the 9th us circuit court of appeals in san 
francisco struck down the fras 2yearold program that required 
railroads to check the members of train crews involved in serious 
accidents for drug or alcohol use the court stated that such tests 
were unconstitutional unless there was a suspicion that an 
individual worker was under the influence of drugs or alcohol 
but last friday us circuit judge thomas tang granted a 
request by the government to stay the order until april 2 tang was 
in the 21 majority that originally voted to invalidate the testing 
riley said that under federal judicial procedures if the 
government files its appeal by april 2 which officials say they 
will the stay would automatically remain in effect until the 
supreme court issues a decision in the case that would probably 
take months 
but a spokesman for the countrys railroad unions said the stay 
would not be automatically extended beyond april 2 edward wytkind 
spokesman for the railway labor executives association said that 
after april 2 the supreme court could decide to allow the tests to 
resume at any time 
we dont view the stay as any sort of attack on employees 
wytkind said its just on an interim basis 
as a result of the decision the government had also halted drug 
and alcohol testing of railroad workers performed for what it 
called reasonable cause in which a supervisor noticed unusual 
behavior by a worker 
such tests also will be resumed riley said 
