<TEXT>
two scientists set a world record for 
concentrating the suns energy with a homemade silver device that 
could help make a practical solarpowered laser officials said 
we consider this a breakthrough because it just hasnt been 
achieved before said bimleshwar gupta of the us energy 
departments solar energy research institute in golden colo 
which paid for the 150000 project 
roland winston a university of chicago physics professor and 
philip gleckman a graduate physics student used a borrowed mirror 
and their solar concentrator to focus sunlight to 60000 times its 
normal intensity on earth the university announced thursday 
that concentration is about three times the previously achieved 
range of 16000 to 20000 times normal intensity said gupta the 
institutes program manager for solar thermal research 
this work opens whole new areas for applications of solar 
energy he said perhaps the solar concentrator could be used 
to power lasers 
most conventional lasers run on electricity he said there are 
no commercially available solarpowered lasers because the 
technology hasnt been developed to harness the suns rays 
efficiently 
in theory gupta said a solarpowered laser would be cheaper to 
operate because conventional lasers require large amounts of 
expensive electricity 
and those advantages would be greater in space he said where 
solar energy isnt weakened by clouds and is more accessible than 
electricity or other types of energy 
gleckman 26 who helped design the solar concentrator on a 
computer said scientists have used sunlight to power lasers 
before but not very efficiently 
we believe this solar concentrator weve built has the 
potential to make a more efficient solarpowered laser it 
would be less costly and more practical said gleckman 
the solar concentrator he helped design was made from an ounce 
of silver in a university machine shop it is hollow and 
coneshaped about half an inch high and a halfinch wide at the 
base he said 
it has a onecentimeter opening at the wide end and a smaller 
opening measuring about one millimeter at the tip gleckman said 
the device is fitted with a lens and contains a special oil that 
boosts light refraction he said 
the 16inch diameter mirror a standard astronomical telescope 
mirror was borrowed from the universitys yerkes observatory 
gleckman said 
the solar concentrators design was based on the principle of 
nonimaging optics developed by winston nearly 15 years ago 
the university said 
in a test feb 12 on the roof of a university physics building 
the solar concentrator achieved an intensity of six kilowatts per 
square centimeter the statement said the previous record was less 
than one kilowatt per square centimeter it said 
