<TEXT>
a private college group urged president reagan 
on friday to sign the civil rights restoration act even though the 
act fails to include a broad exemption for religious schools 
richard f rosser president of the national association of 
independent colleges and universities said his organization was 
the main proponent of efforts that failed in the house to add a 
socalled religious tenet amendment to the bill 
but the association of 800 private institutions including 
catholic and other religiousaffiliated colleges still wants 
reagan to sign the bill which restores the scope of civil rights 
laws restricted by the supreme court in a 1984 case involving grove 
city pa college 
rosser in a letter to reagan said it was made clear during the 
house debate that the legislative intent of the new bill is to 
give deferential treatment to requests for religious exemption 
under title ix 
as the lead organization seeking passage of a religious tenet 
amendment we hope that the religious liberty concerns we 
articulated can be addressed by the congress at a future time 
rosser said 
we want to reiterate our unqualified support for this 
legislation he added 
reagan has repeatedly threatened to veto the legislation which 
was passed by margins of 7514 in the senate and 31598 in the 
house easily enough to override a veto 
the senate approved the bill last month after adding an 
amendment that says nothing in the bill or existing law requires 
any institution to perform or pay for abortions 
the house passed the bill march 2 despite a written warning from 
reagan that he would veto it if it is presented to me in its 
current form 
he said then it dramatically expands the scope of federal 
jurisdiction over state and local governments and the private 
sector and poses a particular threat to religious liberty 
the restoration act specifies that entire institutions and 
government agencies are covered by federal laws protecting the 
civil rights of women minorities the handicapped and the elderly 
if any program or activity within the institutions receives federal 
aid 
the bill exempts farmers getting crop subsidies people on food 
stamps and others receiving federal assistance 
