<TEXT>
about 50 conservationists and residents 
of this scenic philadelphia suburb gathered friday to protest a 
planned power line through a farm made famous by artist andrew 
wyeth 
wyeth who is from chadds ford used the kuerner farm for more 
than 1000 studies and at least five paintings over 45 years 
he spent as much time here as i did farming he painted while 
we worked said karl kuerner jr 61 who raises cattle and grows 
hay on the 35acre farm 
philadelphia electric co plans to place wooden utility poles on 
a 250foot stretch of the farm as part of a 11mile power line 
between a concord substation and kennett square said bill jones a 
spokesman for the company 
growth in the area southwest of philadelphia near the delaware 
state line makes the new line necessary before peak demand in the 
summer he said 
the existing lines in the area were overloaded almost daily 
when the temperature got over 90 last summer jones said adding 
that there were several brief blackouts because of the demand 
philadelphia electric serves 14 electric customers in 
southeastern pennsylvania and northern maryland 
a power line already traverses the kuerner farm with three 
100foot metal towers standing on a meadow near a shingled barn 
the new line would come within 35 feet of the barn kuerner said 
demonstrators holding signs outside the entrance to the kuerner 
farm said an alternate route along a nearby highway would have less 
of an impact on the environment 
route 1 has already got poles and everything its not going 
to affect the aesthetics said harry g haskell jr a former 
mayor of wilmington who grew up with wyeth in chadds ford 
wyeth was ill with the flu and could not attend the 
demonstration said john sheppard a spokesman for the brandywine 
river museum where many of wyeths paintings are displayed 
jl peters a division manager for philadelphia electric said 
the route over the kuerners farm had the least impact 
we are cognizant of the natural beauty of the chadds ford area 
and we have spent considerable time and effort looking at all the 
possible routes through the area so as to minimize the impact on 
the aesthetics peters said 
we are convinced the route we have selected achieves that 
he said 
wyeths paintings using kuerners farm include snow 
flurries which is on display at the national gallery in 
washington evening at kuerners trodden weed pine 
baron and young bull 
he has a special feeling for the land haskell said 
kuerner said wyeth still paints at the farm 
he comes quite often mostly snow scenes he said 
