nine wheaton college graduates go to court monday 
in an attempt to prevent the school from using funds raised by 
alumnae for new coeducational purposes 
the group claims to represent hundreds of alumnae around the 
country upset by the schools plan to admit men this fall for the 
first time in its 154year history 
at issue is 107 million raised by alumnae from 1983 to 1985 in 
a telephone fund drive marking wheatons 150th anniversary says 
alumna mary anne marsh 
the theme of the drive was preparing women for the 21st 
century said marsh we had been given no idea they planned to 
make the school coed 
alumnae first received letters informing them of the plan to go 
coeducational in january 1987 marsh said but she added its 
very clear that this plan was conceived before the first phone was 
picked up 
the trustees of this college of 1200 students 30 miles south of 
boston endorsed the move last may at that time president alice 
emerson said the change was not being made for financial reasons 
but because of a nationwide decline in high school graduates and 
studies showing a waning interest in singlesex colleges 
nancy mccann another of the nine alumnae expressed anger about 
the plan 
its important to keep womens colleges alive she said 
there should be options womens colleges afford women the chance 
to take a real leadership role while they are trying out their 
wings before they go into the real world 
