<TEXT>
us rep mario biaggi and six codefendants 
were greedy thieves who plundered a nowdefunct bronx defense 
contractor for millions of dollars the government charged friday 
as the wedtech corp racketeering trial unfolded 
this is a case about corruption and greed and the purchase and 
sale of public offices it is a case about public officials who 
want to get paid twice once by the people who elected them to do 
their job again by someone else assistant us attorney howard 
wilson told the jury in us district court in manhattan 
this case involves the story of the rise of a little company 
in the bronx that began in 1965 as a machine shop and grew by 
1978 to 15 million in sales by taking advantage of laws that 
promoted the growth of minorityowned enterprises wilson said 
seven years later this company had grown like topsy to a 
defense contractor with 1000 employees and 117 million in 
revenues becoming the biggest single employer in the bronx he 
said 
the success was achieved through corruption and lies 
this case is part of a scandal that also led to the indictment 
of former white house aide lyn nofziger and two former associates 
of attorney general edwin meese iii 
nofziger was convicted last month of lobbying former white house 
associates within one year after he left the government on matters 
including a federal contract for wedtech 
defendants in the manhattan trial are biaggi 70 former bronx 
borough president stanley simon 57 bernard g ehrlich 59 of 
bedford biaggis former law partner and a former major general in 
the new york national guard biaggis son richard 38 of fort lee 
nj peter neglia 39 of armonk the former regional 
administrator of the small business administration john mariotta 
57 scarsdale former wedtech chairman and ronald betso 39 of 
brooklyn a former cop and friend of neglias 
they all treated this company like a gold mine said wilson 
some took a lot some took a little but they all took 
they engaged in the scheme by saying that mariotta who is 
hispanic was the majority owner of wedtech and thus the company 
was entitled to a federal program that allowed companies to get 
government business without bidding the government says 
the minority member of the company must own more than 51 percent 
of the firm but in fact wilson charged mariotta owned less than 
half 
biaggi at one point demanded 5 percent of wedtechs revenues 
but that was too much for wedtech officials wilson said who then 
gave him 5 percent of wedtech stock that was put in his sons name 
at another point biaggi asked for 50000 for expediting a 
lease before the citys board of estimate the prosecutor said and 
the law firm his son worked for received the money the day after 
the lease was signed 
in addition the law firm earned 1 million in retainers fees 
from wedtech from 1978 to 1985 wilson said 
simon who was borough president from 1979 to 1987 demanded and 
received over 50000 that came in cash in envelopes meals chips 
for gambling in atlantic city casinos pink marble in his home a 
trip to rome and contributions in his name to charities wilson 
said 
he also got a job for his brotherinlaw at wedtech and took 
half his raises over the years wilson said 
neglia as regional sba head and then as acting chief of staff in 
washington was wedtechs paidfor friend wilson said 
among other things wilson contended neglia warned the company 
about a congressional inquiry provided navy specifications for 
bidding on a pontoon contract wedtech wanted and helped wedtech 
obtain contracts of increasing value 
neglia was paid with stock options frequent meals 
contributions to the republican party in his name and the promise 
of a job once he left office wilson said less than a month after 
leaving the government in early 1986 he went to work for the law 
firm biaggi and ehrlich 
