an american peace activist held by 
contra rebels for nine days said friday the experience was the 
most terrifying of his life and his captors threatened to kill 
him if he tried to escape 
richard boren a 30yearold witness for peace volunteer from 
elkin nc said he was forced at gunpoint to go with the contras 
after they captured him during an attack march 1 on a northern farm 
cooperative 
they freed him wednesday night suffering from a cold but 
unharmed 
witness for peace based in durham nc opposes us policy on 
nicaragua and support for the rebels and seeks to document contra 
human rights abuses 
the explosions sounded like they were all around literally i 
thought wed end up getting killed boren said of the rebel 
attack on the cooperative 
i heard a shot right at the door to the house i was staying 
in he said i looked up and saw isabel ramos the 13yearold 
girl was wounded 
he said he left the house with his arms raised and was taken 
along with 12 nicaraguans by the contras i asked them if they 
were going to kill me and their response was yes if i ran away 
he added 
boren said his release wednesday night near quilali a village 
170 miles north of managua surprised him he said he plans to go 
back to the united states for a while to see his family and friends 
i have now personally experienced the terror the nicaraguan 
people are subjected to at the hands of the contras he said 
it has been the most terrifying experience of my life and i doubt 
the emotional scars from the experience will ever completely heal 
he was the second american member of witness for peace captured 
by the contras last october the rebels held robert fisher for two 
weeks in central chontales province 
