koko the cover girl gorilla who 
communicates through sign language may be bred with colossus 
reputed to be the largest lowland gorilla in captivity a zoo 
official said friday 
koko whose ability to use sign language and doting upon a pet 
kitten landed her on the cover of national geographic magazine has 
signed to her keepers that she wants to have a baby said penny 
patterson director of the gorilla foundation at woodside calif 
where the ape lives 
she may get that chance with the aptly named 600pound colossus 
who is moving sunday from new hampshire to florida said pat quinn 
president and director of the zoo near this panhandle city 
an initial attempt at breeding may be through artificial 
insemination but quinn said he hoped colossus eventually would be 
able to mate naturally with koko and other females 
semen will be obtained from colossus just before he is flown in 
a chartered dc3 from bensons animal park in hudson nh to 
nearby pensacola and then trucked to the zoo quinn said 
we are hoping to obtain some of that for use with koko because 
she is very anxious to become a mother said ms patterson 
kokos original pet kitten which she named all ball because the 
manx cat had no tail was hit by a truck and killed after the 
national geographic story but koko was given a replacement she 
named smokey now fullgrown 
koko 16 and a male gorilla michael communicate with sign 
language to express their feelings ask for food and certain 
teachers and inquire about other animals 
colossus sperm may be used because captive gorillas sometimes 
develop incest taboos against cage mates so michael would be 
unsuitable ms patterson said also colossus was captured in the 
wild as an infant 20 years ago and isnt inbred with zoo gorillas 
we hope to socialize him so he will breed naturally with 
females quinn said 
colossus has never seen another gorilla outside his original 
family the socialization process would start by letting colossus 
see smell and touch a male chipanzee said quinn then he would be 
introduced to another bachelor male gorilla or a nonproductive 
female before trying to mate him 
quinn said he is working closely with lester fisher director of 
chicagos lincoln park zoo and chairman of the gorilla species 
survival plan for the american association of zoos and aquariums 
fisher a veterinarian said nothing definite has been decided 
on breeding yet but that he was happy to see colossus remain 
within the zoological community because he is the first gorilla in 
a long time to go on the auction block he would provide a new gene 
pool because he was born in the wild 
the plan is designed to develop a selfsustaining captive 
breeding program in north america because the number of animals in 
the wild are dwindling and threatened by encroaching civilization 
after his arrival sunday night colossus will be kept isolated 
for several days with a comingout news conference scheduled for 
friday quinn said 
