eastern airlines embroiled in labor problems 
has been forced to cancel numerous flights because of a shortage of 
pilots and there is no sign the pilot drain is easing an eastern 
executive testified friday 
easterns loss of pilots and details about the impact of that 
loss were disclosed during testimony in a federal court hearing on 
whether eastern should be allowed to go ahead with plans to lease 
26 eastern jets to orion air a north carolina cargo carrier 
the air line pilots association is asking the us court of 
appeals to stop the easternorion deal claiming it is designed to 
circumvent the pilots labor contract eastern has said it wants 
orion to fly the planes with nonunion pilots in case of a strike 
at eastern 
in an attempt to show that eastern is planning to lease only 
spare aircraft to orion the miamibased carrier produced internal 
documents showing a sharp increase in the number of pilots who have 
left the company 
the departures and a high rate of sick leave by pilots at the 
airline are leaving aircraft sitting idle testified william r 
croucher easterns director of planning and administration 
eastern submitted to the court internal documents showing that 
500 pilots left the company for various reasons in 1987 a number 
that croucher said is nearly 10 times the historical average pilot 
attrition rate at the airline 
he said so far this year 259 eastern pilots have either left 
the company or have given notice to depart within 90 days the 
airline anticipates losing a total of 600 pilots this year 
according to croucher 
the pilots union has said previously that the labor turmoil at 
eastern and a push by management to seek labor concessions has 
caused hundreds of pilots to seek early retirement or quit to join 
other airlines even though they are sacrificing their seniority 
the figures provided by eastern in court friday however are 
the first details as to how serious the pilot drain has become at 
the airline which has about 4000 pilots croucher said the 
airline is hiring about 30 pilots a week but that because of long 
training periods the number is inadequate to make up for the 
losses 
croucher said the pilot shortage has forced eastern to cancel 
several thousand flying hours that had previously been scheduled 
for march and april and to cut back total planned flying hours for 
the rest of the year 
during three days last month feb 26 through feb 28 eastern 
canceled a total of 135 singlepoint flights because no cockpit 
crews were available 
judge barrington d parker who is hearing the orioneastern 
case continued the matter until next monday after granting a 
pilots union request for internal eastern documents on various 
eastern aircraft including those that are to be leased to orion 
eastern had refused to turn over the documents claiming that 
they could be used by the pilots union to gain information about 
easterns plans in event of a strike parker directed that the 
documents be made available only to the unions three lawyers and 
two union members and that they not be copied 
