the simbrah association is being added to an 
agriculture department list of registered cattle breeds so owners 
can qualify for higher federal payments when animals are 
slaughtered under the departments brucellosis eradication program 
brucellosis is a highly contagious disease james w glosser 
acting administrator of the departments animal and plant health 
inspection service said friday 
our experience has shown that indemnities encourage owners to 
remove infected animals from their herds to prevent the spread of 
the disease glosser said 
brucellosis can be passed on to humans where it is known as 
undulant fever through raw milk from infected cows 
simbrah cattle are a cross between simmental and brahman the 
department said approximately 2200 us producers own registered 
simbrah cattle 
the indemnity rate for all dairy cattle and registered beef 
cattle and bison is 250 per animal while the payment for 
nonregistered beef and bison is 50 per animal 
officials said the new rule goes into effect on april 11 
