<TEXT>
the government and bell helicopter textron 
signed agreements friday under which the fort worth texas company 
will pay 88 million to settle claims that it overcharged for 
military helicopter spare parts 
the settlement disclosed earlier in the week is considered one 
of the largest ever in a defense contracting case 
it resulted from inaccurate cost accounting information bell 
gave the government from october 1982 to october 1985 the justice 
department said in a statement 
the justice departments civil division and the army each signed 
separate agreements with the company 
during the course of the investigation bell consistently 
maintained that there was no wrongdoing and the us attorneys 
office in fort worth said it notified bell on friday that the 
office has declined criminal prosecution in the case 
that effectively closes our case assistant us attorney 
ron eddins said in fort worth we did that because of all of the 
factors that were disclosed during the investigation their coming 
forward and agreeing to work things out with the pentagon was a 
part of it too 
eddins said the justice departments civil fraud division has 
also issued an agreement with them that accepts the payment and the 
administrative agreement to settle the civil issue the case is 
closed there too 
bell president lm horner said the settlement which he 
described as encompassing issues well beyond those which were 
investigated cleans the slate and will allow for the normalization 
of relations between bell and the army 
under the settlement bell will pay the government 69 million 
within the next 30 days the government will also have its choice 
of about 11 million in spare parts inventory additional 
provisions of the agreement make it worth somewhere in the 
neighborhood of 88 million the pentagons chief spokesman dan 
howard has said 
bell will forgo claims to about 6 million worth of interest on 
contract progress payments withheld by the army and about 15 
million in legal fees offsetting that will be a 11 million 
payment by the army to bell to cover a separate contract that got 
sidelined in the dispute 
maj phil soucy an army spokesman has said most of the 
overcharges came as a result of an accounting system used in 
handling army contracts bell switched to a computerized accounting 
and inventory system that had the effect among other things of 
accelerating the companys requests for army progress payments for 
work performed 
bell agreed to implement a new accounting system that met the 
armys approval in october 1985 
