the environmental protection agency said 
friday it had approved field tests in wisconsin for a genetically 
engineered bacterium designed to improve the ability of alfalfa to 
use nitrogen in the air as a fertilizer 
the bacterium rhizobium meliloti grows naturally on alfalfa 
roots and mutant forms have been used to enhance plant growth in 
the past 
using the techniques of recombinant dna biotechnica inc of 
cambridge mass has reinserted the genes responsible for nitrogen 
use nitrogen fixation back into the organism giving it two 
copies of the genes 
lab and greenhouse tests indicate this will enhance alfalfa 
yield according to an epa announcement when the company applied 
for permission to test 13 months ago 
epa has an active regulatory program for genetically engineered 
pesticides but this bacterium is not a pesticide it is the first 
genetic engineering case under epas authority to regulate new 
chemicals and the test will precede under approval of the 
companys premanufacture notice for a new chemical 
the tests will be conducted in pepin county wis a county 
lying on the mississippi river about 20 miles southwest of eau 
claire 
