the canadian mortgage and housing corp has 
refused to revise building codes that have effectively barred 
american manufactured plywood from being used in canada the 
commerce department said friday 
a change in the canadian building codes is a key part of the 
plywood provisions in the proposed uscanada free trade agreement 
and rep ron wyden dore said that congress will have to get 
tough with the canadians in writing provisions to implement the 
agreement 
rep don bonker dwash said he was disappointed in the 
canadian decision and that while he thought the overall free trade 
agreement was a excellent package on this provision our 
negotiators got taken to the cleaners 
claire buchanan a commerce department spokeswoman declined 
comment but said the decision was under review 
the reagan administration had linked the elimination of plywood 
tariffs on both sides of the border to a revision in construction 
regulations by the cmhc a governmentcontrolled mortgage authority 
canadians insist american plywood is not sturdy enough to 
withstand the harsh climate of canada a claim officials of the 
american plywood industry say is unfounded 
rep peter defazio dore called the canadian refusal 
protectionism plain and simple 
if the administration gives into this they are just 
confirming it will be oneway free trade and that will be a 
disaster for the northwest plywood industry defazio said 
while construction sponsored by chmc accounts for only 10 
percent of canadas construction plywood market administration 
officials had hoped it would be a foot in the door for american 
plywood manufacturers and that changes would eventually be made in 
other building codes that have restricted us imports 
the door got slammed today wyden said this represents a 
major inequity in the free trade agreement and it is just more 
fodder for our position that we need tough enabling legislation 
oregon is the top plywood producing state in the nation 
wyden defazio and other northwest congressmen at a house 
subcommittee hearing earlier this week had warned that the free 
trade agreement would do little to open the canadian market to 
americanmaufactured plywood while at the same time it would give 
canadian plywood manufactuers unrestricted access to american 
markets 
the agreement calls for the total elimination of the 20 percent 
us tariff on canadian plywood and the 15 percent canadian tariff 
on us plywood over 10 years 
wyden and others have suggested that a provision be inserted in 
the treatys implementing language that would call for a review of 
american access to the canadian market before us tariffs are 
totally eliminated 
