<TEXT>
with help from a usled aid 
program a rundown site dividing roman catholic and protestant 
areas of belfast is being transformed into an industrial park for 
fledgling businessmen 
it is one of about 40 projects that have been promised money 
from the multimilliondollar international fund for ireland the 
most tangible outgrowth of the angloirish agreement of 1985 that 
aims to help reconcile feuding catholics and protestants in 
northern ireland 
the 16 milliontownsend enterprise park will create space for 
45 new businesses near the towering peace wall dividing the 
protestant shankill road district from the catholic falls road 
frank murphy the project head said it would not have gone 
forward without the funds 440000 contribution 
but just as the fund is getting off the ground its future has 
been put in question following an announcement that the us state 
department is dropping the fund from its 1989 allocations of the 
funds present kitty of 868 million 85 million has come from 
washington with 35 million more due this year 
the rationale behind the fund is that in a province with a 
17percent unemployment rate and the collapse of its traditional 
heavy industries only economic revival can eliminate slums 
joblessness and resentment 
another project helped by the fund aims at turning the 
firstcentury ruin of navan fort in county armagh into a tourist 
site another has given 4500 to frank odonnell a 24yearold 
londonderry catholic unemployed for two years to open his own 
business selling handcarved fireplace mantels 
when the fund was set up in 1986 the us congress approved 
120 million over three years to stimulate economic regeneration 
and foster catholicprotestant reconciliation seventyfive percent 
was earmarked for northern ireland and 25 percent for border 
counties in the irish republic to the south 
some protestants are suspicious since the angloirish agreement 
grants the irish republican government in dublin a say in their 
affairs the rev ian paisley the northern irish protestant 
hardliner called the fund yankee blood money and urged a 
