<TEXT>
spring has come to central alabama the 
redbuds are blooming the fire ants are pushing up fresh mounds of 
earth and jesse jackson is the peoples choice in dallas county 
where the infamous bloody sunday attack at the edmund pettus 
bridge shocked the nation 23 years ago 
jackson overwhelmed the presidential primary field here tuesday 
23 years and one day after alabama state troopers savagely beat 
black voting rights advocates attempting to march from selma to 
montgomery the episode shown on national television helped 
galvanize congress to pass the federal voting rights act later that 
year 
on tuesday jackson carried alabama by a narrow margin but he 
held better than a 5to1 edge over his nearest democratic 
challenger in dallas county where blacks constitute 55 percent of 
the 50000 residents 
the official county tally showed jackson with 4872 votes to 923 
for the runnerup sen albert gore of tennessee vice president 
george bush easily won the republican race with 1282 votes 
selma mayor joe smitherman who was serving his first term when 
bloody sunday took place said he thinks a lot of white democrats 
didnt vote but would have gone for bush if theyd been able to 
cross over however he acknowledges that blacks gave jackson an 
undeniably smashing victory in selma and dallas county 
the black community really turned out for jesse he was here a 
week before the election and i accompanied him as he walked 
through a poor black section of town said smitherman who 
admits he was a segregationist back when it was fashionable 
you had to be a segregationist to be elected in the south when 
i was starting out said the 58yearold mayor but weve 
matured ive matured we were wrong to try and deny people their 
right to vote and im sorry for what we did 
given the changes that have occurred in selma smitherman said 
its really no surprise jackson did so well 
however the man who led the bloody sunday march rep john 
lewis dga professed amazement that a black could score such a 
victory in dallas county 
to me it is simply unbelievable said lewis when contacted 
at his washington dc office when hosea williams and i led 
that march back in 1965 only 21 percent of dallas countys black 
residents were registered to vote 
since then smitherman points out a lot of the alabama river 
has flowed beneath the edmund pettus bridge 
when i was first elected mayor in 1964 only 50 percent of our 
streets were paved and less than half of our homes were connected 
to the sewage system but after 1965 we started taking advantage of 
the federal programs and grants that existed at the time now 
every street is paved and the sewage system is all over town 
also we now have an appointed black county school 
superintendent who makes more damned money than i do half of the 
city council is black and the assistant police chief is black 
blacks probably have made more progress in selma than in any other 
whitecontrolled city in the alabama 
the rev joseph rembert pastor of browns chapel where the 
bloody sunday march began acknowledges there have been changes in 
selma but he adds that whites still hold most of the power and 
that many of the changes have come about as the result of federal 
court actions initiated by blacks 
attitudes are slowly changing in selma he said but like 
most places weve still got a long way to go what we really need 
here desperately is jobs our county unemployment rate runs about 
16 percent and its probably as high as 25 percent for blacks 
rembert adds though that he would rather be one of selmas 
27000 residents than live in a big northern city like new york 
we dont have a utopia here but at least when we stage a 
protest these days nobody gets hurt blacks and whites may fight to 
the bone over an issue but when its over they also may go off and 
have lunch together and thats a big change from the past 
edwin moss one of the citys three black city councilmen said 
he has seen many changes during the 73 years he has lived in selma 
weve made some big political strides in this county and 
weve made social progress too said moss who founded and 
manages a federal credit union with a largely black membership 
now he added we need economic progress we need jobs we 
need financing for blackowned businesses 
smitherman in the midst of his sixth fouryear term agrees 
selma needs more jobs but hes obviously proud of his city with 
its wide main street and gracious neighborhoods he points out he 
couldnt be mayor without the support of both blacks and whites and 
is quick to show visitors his accomplishments in integrating 
government and improving the local standard of living 
thats why i personally like jesse jacksons message he 
said hes talking about the same things i deal with as mayor 
hes talking about jobs about the problems of working people 
about the homeless and the poor 
you know he said jesse reminds me a lot of george 
wallace 20 years ago theyre both populists 
yet he said neither he nor most other local whites voted for 
jackson last tuesday 
its funny but youll hear a group of whites talking politics 
and somebody will say jesse makes more sense than any of them 
then hell up and add that hes voting for bush or gore a blacks 
just not going to get many white votes around here not yet at 
least smitherman said i dont know why i didnt vote for 
jesse maybe its because i dont think he can win 
at present there is only one elected black county official in 
dallas county which is under a federal court mandate to create 
four voting districts two predominantly white and two 
predominantly black by the fall election 
that one black official is district judge nathaniel walker who 
left selma and got his law degree at fordham university then 
returned home walker the first black to hold countywide office 
here said he is heartened by the changes he has seen in his 
hometown 
i was among the marchers who were attacked on bloody sunday 
he said back then the courthouse was off limits for blacks it 
was a place to be feared 
but jesses victory is an example of what we were fighting 
for last tuesdays election shows that the people recognize just 
how dear is their right to vote and that theyre determined to 
exercise their franchise 
john lewis who was hospitalized for two days with injuries he 
received on bloody sunday said much the same thing 
thats what the civil rights movement was all about lewis 
said we were trying to build a biracial democracy in alabama 
and throughout the south jesse jacksons overwhelming victory in a 
place like selma proves this is possible 
</TEXT>
