<TEXT>
companies making computer hardware and 
communications equipment may be growing rapidly but a private 
survey released today finds many have been less profitable than the 
general run of american companies during recent years 
intense competition from japan and other foreign rivals is one 
reason for the profit squeeze on those companies according to 
harvey poppel a partner in broadview associates of fort lee nj 
the investment banking firm that conducted the survey 
a broadview survey of 269 usbased hardware and equipment 
companies found they had a median return on equity of 65 percent 
in 1987 with a large number of poorly performing small companies 
dragging down the results 
poppel said the median return on equity for major american 
companies is typically about 11 or 12 percent 
return on equity is a widely used measure of a companys 
performance it is the companys profit as a percentage of its 
shareholders equity or net worth 
when the survey results were adjusted to give the heaviest 
weight to the companies with the biggest stock market values such 
as highly profitable international business machines corp the 
average return on equity was 107 percent roughly in line with the 
average for american business 
broadview associates specializes in mergers and acquisitions in 
the computer software and services industry poppel said a survey 
of nearly 200 of those companies found their return on equity was 
above average about 186 percent last year 
poppel cited several reasons for the difficulties of the 
computer hardware and communications equipment companies 
japan and other aggressive competitors are willing to accept 
lower profit margins to gain shares of the world market 
many nations protect their home markets and domestic companies 
especially in the case of western europe with telecommunications 
equipment 
products have short life cycles giving companies only a short 
time to recoup their heavy investments 
it is easy for new companies to enter the market especially at 
the low end because the basic components such as computer chips 
are readily available 
in contrast poppel said the information services companies have 
higher return on equity because their offerings cannot easily be 
rendered obsolete with new technology and are protected by high 
barriers to entry of new competitors 
prices of products such as software and database services can be 
kept relatively high and companies have fewer expensive assets such 
as factories poppel noted 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

