<TEXT>
it was a marketing phenomenon that turned into 
the focus of an international battle with multibilliondollar 
implications 
within a year of introducing its 4500 pony subcompact to north 
america in 1984 hyundai corp of south korea captured 7 percent of 
the canadian market it then invaded the united states and sold 
168182 of its excels in just 10 months 
but were the koreans exploiting a market void or unfairly 
dumping the autos at belowcost prices in order to grab a share of 
the lucrative market 
the canadian import tribunal is considering evidence from four 
weeks of hearings that concluded thursday over claims by domestic 
automakers such as general motors corp and ford motor co of 
unfair pricing by hyundai hyundai could be slapped with a 26 
percent duty if found to be dumping cars 
the case has worldwide implications as americas car giants 
compete against asian rivals whove grabbed more than 25 percent of 
their auto market 
a ruling is expected march 23 and both sides have the right to 
appeal 
in antidumping hearings held in ottawa gm and ford 
subsidiaries in canada accused hyundai of purposely setting 
belowcost prices to grab a niche in the competitive smallcar 
market 
the carmakers asked the canadian import tribunal to uphold 
revenue canadas preliminary finding last november that hyundai has 
been dumping pony excel and stellar hatchbacks and sedans in 
canada at an average 26 percent cheaper than they cost in south 
korea 
a 26percent duty would add more than 1000 to the price of 
hyundais in 182 showrooms across canada and could lead to similar 
cases against other foreign makes 
gm and ford told the tribunal they were forced to slash prices 
and offer cash rebates in order to compete with hyundais 
bargainbasement approach 
future injury is going to take the form of reduced production 
reduced employment and reduced utilization of productive 
capacity penny bonner legal counsel for the two companies 
testified thursday 
hyundai acknowledged using canada as a spearhead to penetrate 
the american market but argued that it never hurt gm or ford 
because the rearwheeldrive pony had no direct competition at the 
bottom end of the market 
the pony was swept along because in a real sense there was no 
competition said hyundai lawyer richard gottlieb he termed the 
success of the nice little car a fluke coming right at the end 
of a recession when american carmakers virtually had given up on 
the subcompact market 
in surprising testimony on thursday lawyers for the canadian 
governments consumer affairs department supported hyundai they 
said the korean company answered a need ignored by north american 
manufacturers thereby helping consumers 
hyundai zoomed to a 21 percent share of the smallcar market in 
canada in 1985 with sales of 79072 ponies and stellars 
but since the preliminary antidumping ruling the canadian 
subsidiary has been in a tailspin and some dealers have resigned 
according to company spokesman greg young 
it destroyed us in the marketplace in terms of public 
perception and confidence in the product young said 
while still the thirdranked import behind honda and toyota 
hyundai expects to sell just 45000 cars this year led by the 
excel which starts at 5835 
people may say i like the honda civic but before making up 
my mind im going to take a look at the excel but the honda 
salesman just says why bother because of the possible duties 
young said 
but he said the bad publicity has not reached the united states 
and american hyundai sales are still climbing after reaching 
263610 cars last year 
to save the day in canada hyundai has launched a here to stay 
and proud of it tv and newspaper advertising campaign 
it pledged to proceed with a 259 million manufacturing plant in 
bromont quebec and 16 million parts factory in newmarket 
ontario scheduled to open later this year the plants will create 
1300 jobs and give hyundai the capacity to make 100000 newmodel 
compacts a year 
the plants will expand a canadian car industry that grew out of 
the milestone 1965 auto pact with the united states which permits 
vehicles and parts to move dutyfree across the border dominated 
by gm ford and chrysler subsidiaries the canadian car and truck 
plants employ 140000 workers with another 400000 related jobs 
young said hyundai will remain in business here but may be 
forced to reassess operations if antidumping duties are imposed 
it may be step one against all import car companies against 
all competition he said 
