an impending battle for media 
general inc is heating up with television producer burt sugarman 
boosting his stake in the company and signaling a fight to force a 
shareholder vote on his 175 billion buyout bid 
sugarman said thursday that two companies he controls boosted 
their stake in media general the virginiabased broadcasting and 
publishing corporation to 10 percent from 98 percent 
sugarman also repeated his contention that media generals board 
of directors was legally bound to put his buyout plan to a 
shareholder vote 
however media general disputed sugarmans contentions on how 
the companys two classifications of stock would be allowed to vote 
on a merger 
media general has 28 million shares of class a common stock 
entitled to one vote each and 559168 class b shares that have 
disproportionate voting rights and elect seven of the companys 10 
directors 
the family of media generals chairman d tennant bryan owns 
71 percent of the companys class b stock 
shortly after sugarman made his 6150pershare takeover offer 
late last month the bryan family said it wasnt interested in 
selling the company 
in a letter sent thursday to media generals president and chief 
executive officer james s evans sugarman contended that under 
media generals charter all shareholders should have equal voting 
rights in deciding on a proposed acquisition of the company by 
someone holding at least 10 percent of its stock 
in all other cases the class b stock would retain its special 
voting rights sugarman contended 
sugarman reiterated that if media general directors failed to 
put the proposed merger before shareholders they will be 
breaching their fiduciary duty 
media general disputed sugarmans claims saying company 
counsel found sugarmans legal reasoning incorrect 
media general said that under its charter any merger would 
require the vote of twothirds of each class of stock in addition 
to the charter requirement the company said virginia law requires 
that a merger be approved by more than twothirds of the class b 
stock 
media general owns a number of daily papers including the 
richmond va timesdispatch and news leader the winstonsalem 
nc journal and the tampa fla tribune plus 32 weeklie in 
southern california and a 40 percent interest in garden state 
newspapers inc which owns 18 dailies and four weeklies in eight 
