the credo of banana republics new travel 
magazine is simple people shouldnt travel halfway around the 
world only to find the same hamburger joints theyve got back home 
we are on the brink of becoming mcglobe warns mel ziegler 
president of the san franciscobased clothier and editorinchief 
of trips a quarterly launched nationwide this week 
ziegler says 300000 customers already have expressed interest 
in 10ayear subscriptions to the magazine which promises to 
lead you down the back alleys of cairo onto forbidden islands or 
through your own hometown in search of stories that will transcend 
the distinctions between traveler and fantasist 
we wanted to publish the worlds first honest travel 
magazine he said in a recent interview if you read most 
travel magazines you get the idea travel is painless nothing ever 
goes wrong we all know nobody ever takes a trip like that 
trips which takes an iconoclastic approach to globetrotting 
is aimed at the same affluent urbanites who made such a success of 
the 10yearold adventurewear company which was sold to the gap 
clothing chain for an undisclosed sum in 1983 
it also attempts to latch onto a recent boom in travel magazines 
