<TEXT>
labor secretary ann mclaughlin today said a 
proposal to raise the federal minimum wage to 505 an hour over 
the next four years may sound like the right thing to do but it 
actually would cause a loss of jobs 
mrs mclaughlin said the proposed increase likely to be 
approved next week by the house education and labor committee 
would be particularly hard on young people with no skills who are 
seeking their first jobs 
this is a tough one 505 an hour im afraid would make 
almost any economist have some jitters mrs mclaughlin said in 
an interview on nbctvs today show the body of economic 
thinking is that the increase in the minimum wage while 
wellintentioned and it sounds like the right thing to do actually 
will cause a loss of jobs particularly impacting on young people 
who need to get into the workforce 
education and labor committee chairman augustus f hawkins 
dcalif scheduled a session next wednesday for final action on 
the minimum wage bill the panel had been unable on thursday to 
address all the amendments to a proposal that was approved by the 
house labor standards subcommittee a week ago 
the subcommittee approved an increase from 335 to 465 an 
hour over a threeyear period with a 50cent raise in 1989 and a 
40cent jump in both 1990 and 1991 
during the full committees hearing rep carl c perkins 
dky proposed an amendment for an increase of another 40 cents in 
1992 in an effort to keep the federal minimum at approximately one 
half of the nations average wage 
the committee approved the perkins amendment on a vote of 1814 
with only two democrats reps austin j murphy of pennsylvania and 
timothy j penny of minnesota joining republicans in opposing the 
proposal 
murphy chairman of the labor standards subcommittee said his 
panel had fashioned a measure which would be acceptable to the full 
house and the senate and possibly the white house 
we dont know what impact the fourth year will have on the 
loss of jobs murphy said 
rep stephen j solarz dny however read from a letter 
written to hawkins by labor secretary ann mclaughlin who said 
senior white house advisers would recommend to president reagan 
that he veto any legislation increasing the minimum wage 
it doesnt matter what we do the executive will be against 
it he said 
rep dick armey rtex who opposes any increase proposed an 
amendment to the perkins measure to raise the base to 20 an hour 
but withdrew it after hawkins called it absurd 
the committee approved 2013 an amendment by rep tommy f 
robinson dark to increase the tip credit for restaurant 
employers 
current law allows employers of workers who regularly receive 
tips such as waiters and waitresses to count the tips as earned 
wages equivalent to 40 percent of the minimum wage 
thus a restaurant owner could pay a worker 201 an hour with 
the remaining 134 40 percent of todays 335anhour minimum 
wage supposed to come from tips 
the robinson proposal would increase the credit to 50 percent 
the senate has a companion bill sponsored by sen edward m 
kennedy dmass chairman of the labor and human resources 
committee which raises the minimum wage to 465 an hour over a 
threeyear period 
