<TEXT>
retail sales boosted by strength in autos 
rose 06 percent in february following a january decline the 
government reported today 
the commerce department said that retail sales rose a seasonally 
adjusted 714 million to 12799 billion last month 
while the february increase was generally in line with 
expectations the government revised the january report to show a 
small decline of 02 percent instead of an originally reported 
increase of 05 percent 
even with the january decline analysts said the retail sales 
report generally reflected that the october stock market crash has 
had little effect on consumer buying plans 
ever since the record 508point drop in stock prices which 
occurred on oct 19 economists have been closely watching to see 
whether the consumer sector would weaken 
since consumer spending accounts for twothirds of overall 
economic activity any significant faltering in this area could 
topple the country into a recession 
continued strong gains in employment growth have apparently 
calmed initial jitters over the stock market many economists have 
recently revised up their growth forecasts for 1988 
the february report said that retail sales rose to the highest 
monthly total since august 1987 
much of the strength came from a 16 percent rise in auto sales 
which followed an even stronger 2 percent increase in new car sales 
in january 
without the gain in autos which accounted for almost onefourth 
of total sales last month retail sales would have risen a smaller 
03 percent in february 
the important general merchandise category which includes 
department store sales suffered a 16 percent decline in sales in 
february following a small 01 percent drop in january sales 
