oil prices may be headed higher again after 
months of declines amid swelling inventories and lackluster demand 
analysts say prospects of good summer demand and indications 
that major producers might take action to help curb the recent 
slide should help boost prices in coming months 
unconfirmed reports that the organization of petroleum exporting 
countries was studying a plan to shave 850000 barrels from its 
daily production sent futures contracts soaring on thursday and 
that rally continued today 
near midday on the new york mercantile exchange contracts for 
april delivery of west texas intermediate the benchmark us 
crude stood at 1619 per 42gallon barrel up 19 cents from 
thursday when the price closed up 51 cents at 1600 
refined products also built on thursdays strong advance 
wholesale heating oil up 090 cent thursday stood at 4444 cents 
per gallon up another 051 cent wholesale unleaded gasoline stood 
at 4555 cents per gallon up 041 cent after leaping 114 cents 
per gallon to close at 4514 cents thursday 
james steel an analyst at refco inc commodities said traders 
were encouraged by reports that opec was considering cutbacks even 
though cartel officials later denied that the purported idea of 5 
percent output cuts for all 13 members except iraq was getting 
serious consideration 
the organization of petroleum exporting countries also indicated 
that its pricing committee was unlikely to meet soon despite calls 
by member venezuela for a meeting 
but steel said futures traders pushed prices higher because the 
reports suggested the cartel was at least taking some action to 
deal with the declines before they started getting out of hand 
in the persian gulf for example crude recently has been 
selling at levels between 13 and 14 per barrel far below opecs 
18perbarrel target while in the united states west texas 
intermediate has been bouncing in the 15to16 range after 
selling near 18 in january 
analysts have blamed the slump on sluggish worldwide demand and 
swelling inventories worsened by an unusually warm winter in 
europe 
some opec members desperate to preserve their market shares 
have aggravated the decline by discounting prices to lure customers 
away from opec competitors and nopec countries such as mexico 
britain norway and a host of other smaller nations 
dillard spriggs president of the petroleum analysis ltd 
consulting firm said crude prices could fall another dollar in two 
weeks if world production does not slow down quickly 
in a worstcase scenario buyers might then disappear to wait 
for even lower prices heightening downward price pressure 
but chances are probably pretty good theyll rein it in 
spriggs said citing prospects for increased summer demand i 
think were in this cycle of upanddown that will go on until 
about 1990 
analysts said opecs problem was that the production quotas the 
cartel set at its december meeting simply were too high 
since december opecs official aggregate quota has stood at 
175 million barrels a day spriggs said the cartel would have to 
cut production to about 168 million barrels daily to match demand 
and bring prices back to its 18perbarrel target 
as a result cartel members had to discount the extra barrels to 
sell them said ed krapels of the washingtonbased energy security 
analysis inc consulting firm 
still krapels said the worst is over because demand 
should pick up during the summer driving season 
we expect the situation to be a little easier for opec to 
handle in the next three months than in the last three he said 
at the oppenheimer amp co securities firm oil analyst paul ting 
said he also believed oil prices will head higher continuing in a 
cycle of strengths and weakness 
opec is all too aware of the billions of dollars of income it 
lost by casting off production constraints in 1986 he said 
back in 1985 nobody in his right mind would have thought oil 
could drop below 18 a barrel they got quite a surprise when it 
got down to 8 i think theyre not likely to repeat that again 
ting said 
i think theyre going to get their acts together because 
they really cant live at prices significantly below 18 for a long 
time he said 
