<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880311-0315 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the new york stock exchanges 5weekold 
collar on computerized trading appears to be an effective 
therapy for easing volatility in the postcrash market and luring 
back frightened investors analysts say 
but the restriction also makes the market less attractive to 
investors who thrive on risk which could drive them overseas 
and some market experts even argue that the restriction would do 
little to squelch another panic 
the collar as nyse officials call it has played a role in 
blunting runaway moves in the dow jones industrial average since it 
was enacted feb 4 judging from the markets behavior since then 
it works by banning use of the exchanges computers for a 
trading technique known as index arbitrage when the dow average 
moves 50 points from the previous close an earlier voluntary 
restraint was triggered by a 75point change 
since the 50point collar was announced it has never been 
breached the dow average approached it three times moving up 
4758 on feb 10 up 4841 on feb 29 and down 4824 on thursday 
i think its got to be more than coincidence that it doesnt 
get to 50 said richard wholey a brokeranalyst at the wayne 
hummer amp co investment firm in chicago i would say theres got 
to be a very strong connection 
by comparison in precollar days the dow average jumped 7642 
points jan 4 fell 14058 points jan 8 and fell 5720 points jan 
20 it exceeded a 50point swing six times in december and four 
times in november 
last october when the market suffered the worst decline since 
the great crash of 1929 the dow average careened over 50 points 12 
times capped by the unprecedented 508 point plunge on black 
monday oct 19 
some wall street strategists knowledgeable about index arbitrage 
believe the collar directly influences market behavior when index 
arbitrage traders see the dow average moving 40 or more points 
beyond the previous close they turn off the computers that run the 
automatic trading programs 
the limit is a definite factor said leigh stevens stock 
index futures strategist at painewebber inc in new york the 
traders will see they are near it theyll stop at that point 
because if its going to touch 50 theyd be forbidden to use it 
for the rest of the day 
index arbitrage enables investors to sell massive volumes of 
stock in new york and simultaneously buy the equivalent stockindex 
futures traded in chicago or vice versa in an attempt to profit 
from price differences 
the technique has been blamed for playing a role in the wall 
street crash and subsequent price swings that frightened millions 
of ordinary investors 
several prominent wall street firms concerned they were killing 
their own business and arousing congressional hostility have since 
abandoned index arbitrage for their own accounts 
i dont see anything under the surface thats detrimental 
about the new york stock exchanges limitation said john a 
conlon jr executive vice president and director of institutional 
equity research at nikko securities co international in new york 
any step toward attempting to quell the kind of volatility we saw 
is an intelligent posture 
others agreed but said the limit was discouraging speculators 
who thrive on the risky futures markets this has helped cause a 
drop in the futures business and raised fears that less restrictive 
foreign markets will benefit 
i consider the collar a stabilizer and from the point of view 
of the country or market as a whole its very positive said 
haskel b benishay an economics professor and market expert at 
northwestern universitys kellogg graduate business school 
but of course its less exciting and creates less 
opportunities for index arbitrage program traders to make money 
he said 
some futures experts believe the nyses move reflects a broader 
failure by the securities business to take coordinated steps aimed 
at averting another market collapse a key recommendation of a 
presidential commission 
the critics say the nyses collar wont mesh with the 
circuitbreaking mechanisms imposed in the futures market since the 
crash 
new price limits established to regulate stock index futures 
trading on chicago exchanges could theoretically paralyze those 
markets in response to a sharp decline in prices in such a case 
traders would rush to dump stocks on the nyse which would be 
prevented by its collar from relieving the pressure 
if we should have a sharp market break the markets would 
unlink automatically alger b chapman chairman of the chicago 
board options exchange told an annual futures industry meeting in 
florida earlier this week it would be worse than in october 
 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

